## 2. Talk to your students 1:1 or send personalized emails encouraging them to take the exam 

This can be especially valuable with the girls or underrepresented minorities in your class. They are less likely to be given personal encouragement by teachers and parents, and <a href="https://www.forbes.com/sites/traceywelsonrossman/2019/08/26/new-ncwit-study-outlines-roadmap-for-bringing-more-girls-into-tech/#3ff70bd665a3", target=_"blank">your support is vital</a> to boosting their confidence. 

Interested in more strategies for recruiting girls? [Check out our tips and resources!](http://code.org/girls)

## 3. Send home this flyer 

Or tell your students to <a href="https://code.org/educate/csp/ap-students", target=_"blank">check out this website</a>.

<a href="https://code.org/files/ap-student-flyer.pdf", target=_"blank"><img src="/images/ap-student-flyer.png" width="25%"/></a>

## 4. Ask your students to help spread the word

Have some of your students already signed up? Encourage them to tell other students in the class that they are taking the exam and inspire their friends (on social media or in the class).

## 5. Give them the facts

Taking the exam can save your students money in college credits, help strengthen their college applications, and <a href="https://files.eric.ed.gov/fulltext/ED519365.pdf", target=_"blank">students who take the AP Exam are more likely to graduate from college</a> than their counterparts who don’t — whether or not they pass.


